node.text:
I hope you are all having a good summer!
While I’m glad that many of us can finally enjoy the lighter side of life again, please let’s not forget about all of our fellow humans who are suffering from war, hunger, or natural catastrophes all around the world.
If you are able to aford it: please consider donating to a charity.

Just two picks of the many, many worthy organizations out there:
@doctorswithoutborders, who continue their heroic work to ease human suffering in some of the worlds most dire places.

And if you want to help the victims of the devastating flood in western Germany:

Aktionsbündnis Katastrophenhilfe
Spendenkonto:
Commerzbank
IBAN: DE65 100 400 600 100 400 600
BIC: COBADEFFXXX
Stichwort: ZDF Hochwasser
Online-Spenden: aktionsbuendnis-katastrophenhilfe.de

(thanks to @dunjahayali and @ruthe_offiziell for bringing it to my attention )

node.text:
My cover for this week’s @newyorkermag .

I also did short Q&A with art editor Francoise Mouly about drawing trees.
(My main insight comes from watching the great Bob Ross. To get trees right I first have to manage to loosen up and (this is very very hard:) be in a good mood).

node.text:
Silkscreen „Voices of Change“ (two versions day/night)
4 color print, signed and numbered 
Available in my Webshop (see recent story or link in bio)

The drawing was published on the cover of the New Yorker a year ago. This view from Brooklyn into Manhattan is one of the things I miss terribly. I hope I can be back later this year!

node.text:
Drawings about living with Parkinson's for the @nytimes
A wonderful (and witty and heartbreaking and funny) exchange between Veronique Viennese and my friend, mentor and hero Steve Heller.
They talk about how they first dealt with the diagnosis, about coping, the difficulties of sharing with their children and how it impacts their productivity as writers.

See recent story for the link to the article.
